      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: Anker Cable Organizer Kit</h2>
      <p>If you do not need a full enclosure and just want to tame loose cables, the Anker organizer kit costs about half as much and includes magnetic cable ties, silicone cable sleeves, and a set of adhesive clips. It will not hide a power strip, but if your power strip already lives under your desk on the floor, this kit handles the visible mess above the surface. The silicone sleeves are particularly good for bundling monitor and charging cables into a single neat run.</p>
      <p>The tradeoff is that there is no box, so adapters and the strip itself remain visible. The magnetic ties are reusable and strong, but they are best for cables that run along metal desk frames — on wood they need the adhesive mounts, which are decent but not as repositionable as the clips in the winning kit. For under-desk cable runs and travel use, it is excellent value. For a fully hidden power setup, you need the box.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>Start by measuring what you actually need to hide. Lay your power strip and the bulkiest adapter you own side by side, then add two inches for cable routing slack. That measurement is the minimum interior length your box needs. Buying a box that is too small is the most common mistake — you end up with adapters bulging out the slots and the lid will not close, which looks worse than no box at all. If you use oversized laptop chargers or multi-port USB gaN chargers, go larger than you think you need.</p>
      <p>Ventilation is non-negotiable. Power adapters generate real heat, and a sealed plastic box acts as an oven. Look for ventilation slots in the lid or sides, and avoid any box marketed as "fully enclosed" or "dust-proof" if you plan to put charging bricks inside. The safe rule is that you should be able to feel airflow when you hold your hand over the lid while devices are charging. If the box is warm to the touch after an hour, it is not ventilated enough.</p>
      <p>Finally, do not skip the clips. Most people buy a box, hide the strip, and wonder why their desk still looks messy. The dangling last foot of each cable is the real problem, and only adhesive clips solve it. Route every cable along the back edge or under-desk rail so nothing hangs freely. A $10 set of clips does more for desk appearance than a $40 box alone.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">evaluation methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Are cable management boxes a fire hazard?</summary>
          <p>A sealed unventilated box can trap heat from power adapters and is a real concern. Look for boxes with ventilation slots or a slatted lid. Do not overload a single box with more than one high-wattage charging brick, and never daisy-chain power strips inside a closed box.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Do adhesive cable clips damage desk finishes?</summary>
          <p>Quality 3M-style adhesive removes cleanly from finished wood, laminate, and metal if you heat it slightly with a hair dryer before peeling. Cheap generic adhesive can leave residue or pull finish off raw wood. Test on an unseen spot first if your desk is expensive.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What size cable management box do I need?</summary>
          <p>Measure your power strip plus the bulkiest adapter plugged into it, and add 2 inches of slack for cable routing. A box rated for 13 inches fits most 8-10 outlet surge protectors with room for wall warts. If you use oversized laptop chargers, go larger rather than cramming everything in.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

